WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:04.340
Okay. Good afternoon, everyone.

2
00:00:05.440 --> 00:00:07.900
On behalf of my co-chair, Ling Kai,

3
00:00:09.140 --> 00:00:11.960
I would like to start this session. My name is Christoph Kuiper.

4
00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:15.660
I'm from Aachen, Germany. Ling Kai is from Duke

5
00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:18.130
University, and we are very

6
00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:21.340
much looking forward to share this session.

7
00:00:22.660 --> 00:00:26.380
And we have seven speakers on the

8
00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:27.140
topic of

9
00:00:28.060 --> 00:00:31.300
transcriptional regulation and cell fate decision in cancer.

10
00:00:32.420 --> 00:00:36.280
And I would, without further ado, would like to call up the

11
00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:36.980
first speaker,

12
00:00:37.860 --> 00:00:41.120
Riley Walter, who will talk on SOX2 as a master

13
00:00:41.180 --> 00:00:44.500
regulator of classical squamous cell carcinoma.

14
00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:55.420
Okay. Hi, everyone. Thank you so much for

15
00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:58.980
being here today, and thank you to the co-chairs and

16
00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:03.000
for AACR for inviting me to give this talk.

17
00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:04.481
I'm really excited to be here.

18
00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:09.320
I have nothing to disclose.

19
00:01:11.300 --> 00:01:15.220
So I study squamous cell carcinoma, or SCC, which is

20
00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:19.360
a major global health burden that results in over one million deaths per

21
00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:23.320
year. An SCC can arise from many tissues of origin,

22
00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:27.000
including the cervix, esophagus, head and neck, and lung.

23
00:01:27.620 --> 00:01:31.480
And current treatments for SCC are aggressive and

24
00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:35.360
invasive, including surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation.

25
00:01:35.790 --> 00:01:39.240
And what's particularly concerning is that there's been very limited

26
00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:43.300
success with current immunotherapies and targeted therapies, which

27
00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:47.110
highlights that there's a lot of room for growth and improvement in treating this

28
00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:50.539
aggressive cancer type. And if we want to improve

29
00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:54.100
treatments, we need to first better understand the underlying

30
00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:55.640
molecular vulnerabilities.

31
00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:01.060
So SCC has a lot of complex genetic

32
00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:02.060
heterogeneity.

33
00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:06.660
And the Hayes group at UNC and later the

34
00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:10.539
Cancer Genome Atlas Consortium were working to try to better

35
00:02:10.581 --> 00:02:14.560
subclassify these tumors, and they decided to use differential gene

36
00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:18.160
expression and ultimately found four subtypes of

37
00:02:18.260 --> 00:02:21.850
SCC: atypical, classical, mesenchymal, and

38
00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:25.760
basal. And with the onset of single-cell sequencing

39
00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:29.680
technologies, they realized that the mesenchymal subtype of tumors were largely

40
00:02:29.740 --> 00:02:31.760
comprised of immune cells and fibroblasts.

41
00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:35.920
So there's three main subtypes recognized today: atypical, classical, and

42
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.660
basal. And though this data is from head and neck SCC, these

43
00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:43.560
subtypes strongly correlate with those found in lung squamous

44
00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:46.500
cancers as well as esophageal squamous cancers.

45
00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:50.980
And this leads me to the question of what are the drivers of these SCC

46
00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:51.700
subtypes?

47
00:02:54.820 --> 00:02:57.960
So one hallmark of squamous cancers at large is

48
00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:00.400
amplification of the chromosome 3q.

49
00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:04.560
So when we break down TCGA patient copy number

50
00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:08.560
data into subtypes: atypical, basal, and classical, we

51
00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:12.520
can see that all of these subtypes harbor

52
00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:16.580
arm level 3q amplification. However, when we zoom in

53
00:03:16.620 --> 00:03:19.780
closer to the 3q locus, we can see one

54
00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:24.520
clear focal amplification that is found only in the classical subtype,

55
00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:28.720
and this occurs at the gene locus for the transcription factor SOX2.

56
00:03:30.260 --> 00:03:34.040
And so because we saw this selective focal amplification at the SOX2

57
00:03:34.060 --> 00:03:37.780
locus, we wanted to know if maybe there was some sort of selective

58
00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:41.620
dependency on SOX2 and/or other transcription factors.

59
00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:45.540
So we turned to the DepMap Gene Effects database and saw right

60
00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:49.570
away that only in the classical subtype do they have

61
00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:53.010
a strong dependency on SOX2 for their growth and

62
00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:53.870
proliferation.

63
00:03:56.320 --> 00:04:00.120
And this leads me to hypothesize that SOX2 is a master regulator of the

64
00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:02.360
classical subtype of squamous cell carcinoma.

65
00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:08.329
So the model system that I used to generate all of the data in this talk today

66
00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:12.329
are two SCC cell lines. And I validated these findings

67
00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:15.730
in other cell lines, but for time and simplicity, we'll just focus on these

68
00:04:15.780 --> 00:04:19.671
two. So we have Kyse-140, which is a SOX2 high,

69
00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:23.520
more classical-like cell line, and Bhy, which is SOX2 low and more

70
00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:27.060
basal-like. And in Bhy, the basal-like, we can

71
00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:30.740
overexpress SOX2 under a doxycycline-inducible promoter.

72
00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:35.460
And then in Kyse-140, the SOX2 high, we can knock down SOX2

73
00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:38.200
expression using CRISPRi or CRISPR inhibition.

74
00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:44.060
And because SOX2 is a transcription factor that can bind to DNA and

75
00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:48.080
activate gene expression, we wanted to know if SOX2 could regulate the

76
00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:51.760
classical SCC gene signature. And these

77
00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:55.480
genes are those that are upregulated in the classical subtype of

78
00:04:55.540 --> 00:04:58.880
tumors from TCGA compared to atypical or basal.

79
00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:03.340
And a pathway analysis on this gene signature includes many interesting pathways

80
00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:06.840
like reactive oxygen species, glycolysis, and xenobiotic

81
00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:07.640
metabolism.

82
00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:12.160
So when I performed RNA sequencing on the overexpression and

83
00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:15.920
knockdown model, we saw that when SOX2 is overexpressed, there's a

84
00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:19.770
significant upregulation of the classical SCC gene signature,

85
00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:23.360
and when SOX2 is knocked down, there is a significant downregulation.

86
00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:30.820
Now, we wanted to dive into the underlying mechanism for this

87
00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:34.500
dependency. And it's known that SOX2 can act as a pioneer

88
00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:38.550
factor that remodels and binds nucleosomes directly in stem cells in

89
00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:42.520
developmental contexts, but we weren't sure if that was happening in SCC because

90
00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:46.020
many of the binding partners, like Oct4, are not expressed in these cells.

91
00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:50.520
So I performed ATAC and SOX2 ChIP sequencing in my knockdown

92
00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:54.200
model and found that there were thousands of sites that lose

93
00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:58.190
accessibility upon SOX2 knockdown, and that these

94
00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:01.980
sites that lose accessibility are preferentially bound by SOX2 and exhibit the

95
00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:06.100
strongest SOX2 binding intensity, leading us to conclude that SOX2 binding

96
00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.120
is necessary for maintaining chromatin accessibility at these

97
00:06:09.180 --> 00:06:12.850
sites.And when we do the converse experiment where we

98
00:06:12.930 --> 00:06:15.110
overexpress SOX2 in BHY,

99
00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:19.990
we can see again thousands of sites that gain accessibility.

100
00:06:20.190 --> 00:06:24.150
And zooming into these gained de novo accessible regions,

101
00:06:24.250 --> 00:06:27.690
we can see a lot of strong SOX2 binding and

102
00:06:27.790 --> 00:06:31.030
also strong SOX2 binding and accessibility in

103
00:06:31.070 --> 00:06:34.910
Kwyz140, which is the classical model, leading us to conclude that

104
00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:37.550
SOX2 overexpression is sufficient to drive chromatin

105
00:06:37.590 --> 00:06:39.490
accessibility.

106
00:06:41.010 --> 00:06:44.650
So we now know that SOX2 binds and maintains

107
00:06:44.670 --> 00:06:48.630
chromatin accessibility at thousands of loci in the genome, but how does this

108
00:06:48.650 --> 00:06:50.200
relate back to gene expression?

109
00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:55.210
Another finding from the SOX2 ChIP-sequencing analysis is that SOX2

110
00:06:55.230 --> 00:06:58.730
predominantly binds to enhancer elements rather than promoters.

111
00:06:58.750 --> 00:07:02.550
So when we wanted to try to identify the direct target genes of SOX2 binding

112
00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:06.130
sites, we used a method called HiChIP, which captures

113
00:07:06.190 --> 00:07:09.750
enhancer-promoter interactions or loops to more precisely link

114
00:07:09.830 --> 00:07:13.210
SOX2-bound enhancers to the promoters of their target genes.

115
00:07:13.619 --> 00:07:17.610
And in this example here at the NOX4 gene locus, you can see in the top track

116
00:07:17.690 --> 00:07:19.710
SOX2 ChIP-sequencing binding sites.

117
00:07:20.490 --> 00:07:24.090
There are lots of strong interactions denoted by the darker green color

118
00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:27.970
between SOX2-bound enhancers and the promoter of this gene.

119
00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:31.790
But when we knock down SOX2, those interactions are lost or

120
00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:35.490
decrease, and this happens across all SOX2 direct target

121
00:07:35.530 --> 00:07:39.430
genes, which not only increases our confidence that this list

122
00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:42.390
we have is direct targets but also

123
00:07:43.310 --> 00:07:46.820
tells us the importance of SOX2 for maintaining these interactions.

124
00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:55.180
So far, I've showed evidence that SOX2 directly regulates accessibility,

125
00:07:55.190 --> 00:07:58.330
enhancer-promoter loops, and gene expression of the classical gene

126
00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:02.280
signature. But how is this gene signature helping the classical cells or

127
00:08:02.310 --> 00:08:04.570
giving them some fitness advantage?

128
00:08:05.190 --> 00:08:08.930
So I performed another pathway analysis on this list of SOX2

129
00:08:08.990 --> 00:08:12.510
direct target genes and again saw enrichment of many

130
00:08:12.610 --> 00:08:15.730
oxidative stress-related pathways like hypoxia,

131
00:08:15.870 --> 00:08:19.130
glycolysis, xenobiotic metabolism, and apoptosis.

132
00:08:19.609 --> 00:08:23.330
And something that these gene pathways have in common is

133
00:08:23.690 --> 00:08:27.610
ferroptosis, which is a form of pre-programmed cell death that

134
00:08:27.670 --> 00:08:31.190
occurs when there's an accumulation of peroxidized lipids.

135
00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:35.750
And looking even closer at this list of SOX2 direct targets, we

136
00:08:35.810 --> 00:08:39.691
see several suppressors of ferroptosis that are upregulated by

137
00:08:39.711 --> 00:08:42.970
SOX2, including GPX2, GSR,

138
00:08:43.211 --> 00:08:46.390
AKR1C3, SLC25A10.

139
00:08:48.070 --> 00:08:51.970
And another piece of data that I have was that classical

140
00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:55.670
SEC cells are more resistant to this drug, an

141
00:08:56.150 --> 00:09:00.130
inducer of ferroptosis, ML162. So these cells are

142
00:09:00.190 --> 00:09:01.590
more resistant

143
00:09:02.570 --> 00:09:04.050
than the basal or atypical.

144
00:09:04.890 --> 00:09:08.490
And this, combined with the upregulation of ferroptosis

145
00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:12.530
suppressors and those other oxidative

146
00:09:12.570 --> 00:09:16.250
stress-related pathways, leads me to hypothesize that SOX2

147
00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:19.390
mediates resistance to ferroptosis in classical SEC.

148
00:09:20.310 --> 00:09:23.910
And so to test this, I performed C11 BODIPY staining in

149
00:09:23.930 --> 00:09:27.840
SOX2 knockdown cells. And the C11 dye is a pH sensor that

150
00:09:27.890 --> 00:09:31.119
turns from red to green in the presence of oxidized lipids.

151
00:09:31.610 --> 00:09:35.410
And so this kind of shift that we see in the

152
00:09:35.430 --> 00:09:38.860
SOX2 knockdown cells to have more green indicates that there's

153
00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:42.710
more peroxidized lipids that form in cytoplasm

154
00:09:42.720 --> 00:09:44.650
after ML162 treatment.

155
00:09:46.730 --> 00:09:50.210
And I also measured cell death using an Annexin 5 and 7-AAD

156
00:09:50.350 --> 00:09:54.250
staining in classical cells with and without ML162 treatment

157
00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:58.450
and saw a significant increase in early apoptosis and almost

158
00:09:58.510 --> 00:10:01.890
twice as much late apoptosis in SOX2 knockdown cells than

159
00:10:01.970 --> 00:10:05.910
controls. And an important caveat of this assay is that it cannot

160
00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:09.810
distinguish between ferroptosis and apoptosis, but I do still

161
00:10:09.830 --> 00:10:13.490
think these findings suggest some sort of involvement of SOX2 in

162
00:10:13.510 --> 00:10:14.330
ferroptosis.

163
00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:20.370
So in summary, today, I've told you that SEC can be

164
00:10:20.390 --> 00:10:24.080
classified into three molecular subtypes, classical, basal, and

165
00:10:24.110 --> 00:10:27.679
atypical, all with unique genomic profiles and vulnerabilities.

166
00:10:28.450 --> 00:10:32.290
And that classical SEC displays a focal amplification of the SOX2

167
00:10:32.330 --> 00:10:36.270
locus and a selective dependency on SOX2 for growth

168
00:10:36.290 --> 00:10:37.100
and proliferation.

169
00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:41.990
SOX2 drives expression of the classical gene signature by regulating

170
00:10:42.010 --> 00:10:45.490
chromatin accessibility and enhancer-promoter interactions.

171
00:10:46.190 --> 00:10:49.840
And finally, SOX2 target genes could be involved with the mediation of

172
00:10:49.870 --> 00:10:51.390
ferroptosis resistance.

173
00:10:52.650 --> 00:10:56.310
I'd like to thank my lab, especially my advisor, Zhao Yang, and Yue-Chan Song,

174
00:10:56.390 --> 00:10:59.770
who's the postdoc that has performed a lot of TCGA analysis I

175
00:10:59.790 --> 00:11:03.290
presented. I'd like to thank my collaborators for their help with the

176
00:11:03.310 --> 00:11:07.210
ferroptosis arm of my project, my funding, my F31 HCI

177
00:11:07.290 --> 00:11:09.570
Travel Award for allowing me to be here.

178
00:11:09.970 --> 00:11:13.450
And I want to give a shout-out to my lab mate, Emily Wilson, who's presenting a

179
00:11:13.490 --> 00:11:17.430
poster on Wednesday about the dual enhancer-promoter function of alternative

180
00:11:17.450 --> 00:11:18.030
promoters.

181
00:11:24.750 --> 00:11:28.110
Thank you very much. So this paper is open for discussion.

182
00:11:28.570 --> 00:11:29.850
Are there any questions?

183
00:11:32.050 --> 00:11:33.790
Maybe I can start with one. So

184
00:11:35.110 --> 00:11:39.090
SOX2 as a transcription factor is also involved in gene regulation

185
00:11:39.110 --> 00:11:42.070
of fetal programs. Could you maybe speculate

186
00:11:42.150 --> 00:11:45.900
how much of that is recapitulated with the

187
00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:47.730
SOX2 phenotype in this cancer?

188
00:11:48.890 --> 00:11:52.860
Yeah. SOX2 is definitely known to be a strong regulator in development and

189
00:11:52.930 --> 00:11:56.830
fetal programs. I've done a principal component

190
00:11:56.910 --> 00:12:00.470
analysis of SOX2 binding in SEC cells versus human

191
00:12:00.530 --> 00:12:04.490
embryonic stem cells, and they do seem to have very different binding profiles,

192
00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:07.750
and I think a lot of that could be due to expression of cofactors.

193
00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:11.410
I briefly mentioned this, but other

194
00:12:12.150 --> 00:12:15.654
stem... binding partners of SOX2, like Oct4, are not

195
00:12:15.694 --> 00:12:19.034
expressed in the SEC cell lines we see here.

196
00:12:19.134 --> 00:12:22.714
So I think that a lot of the difference in binding and genomic

197
00:12:23.234 --> 00:12:24.714
programs could be due to that.

198
00:12:25.884 --> 00:12:26.634
Okay. Thank you very much.

199
00:12:27.934 --> 00:12:31.554
Maybe I'll ask another question. So the loss of

200
00:12:31.574 --> 00:12:34.914
SOX2 will induce both apoptosis and ferroptosis?

201
00:12:36.214 --> 00:12:40.134
It seems like there is some ferroptosis, or some

202
00:12:40.574 --> 00:12:43.954
apoptosis in that last slide in just normal

203
00:12:44.314 --> 00:12:47.254
SOX2 knockdown cells without any ML162.

204
00:12:47.314 --> 00:12:50.554
There is about twice as much apoptosis in those cells.

205
00:12:50.614 --> 00:12:54.234
However, it was 2% compared to 1% in the control

206
00:12:54.294 --> 00:12:57.794
cells. So I think there could definitely be both

207
00:12:57.834 --> 00:13:01.094
apoptosis and ferroptosis happening, but maybe the

208
00:13:01.154 --> 00:13:05.054
advantage that SOX2 is giving these classical

209
00:13:05.094 --> 00:13:08.574
subtype of cells is it's helping them kind of resist this

210
00:13:08.714 --> 00:13:10.054
oxidative stress more.

211
00:13:10.894 --> 00:13:14.874
Have you ever tried any of the inhibitors in label, like ferroptosis

212
00:13:14.954 --> 00:13:15.634
inducers?

213
00:13:16.274 --> 00:13:18.354
Not yet, but we're definitely thinking about it.

214
00:13:19.894 --> 00:13:20.294
Thanks.

215
00:13:21.514 --> 00:13:25.494
I have a question. So Riley, when you knock out SOX2,

216
00:13:25.614 --> 00:13:29.574
do you actually get cells that will grow long-term in tissue culture that

217
00:13:29.594 --> 00:13:33.574
are completely SOX2 deficient? And if so, do they show a change

218
00:13:33.614 --> 00:13:37.234
in cell morphology? I noticed the EMT was on your list, but do they

219
00:13:37.314 --> 00:13:40.374
actually assume a more epithelioid type morphology?

220
00:13:41.214 --> 00:13:45.194
Yeah. So we are able to culture SOX2 knockdown cells

221
00:13:45.234 --> 00:13:48.534
for a long period of time, like about two weeks or so.

222
00:13:49.674 --> 00:13:53.314
And I do not see any changes in morphology in the

223
00:13:53.374 --> 00:13:57.054
SOX2 knockdown. And similarly, when I overexpress SOX2 for

224
00:13:57.114 --> 00:14:00.764
about two weeks or more, I do not see any changes in morphology there as

225
00:14:00.854 --> 00:14:04.594
well. I know that EMT keeps showing up in these lists, and I'm

226
00:14:04.674 --> 00:14:08.274
curious about it, but because we don't see the actual change in morphology,

227
00:14:09.354 --> 00:14:12.824
we're still considering it, but it's not our favorite hypothesis right now.

228
00:14:12.854 --> 00:14:13.774
Okay. Thank you very much.

229
00:14:13.834 --> 00:14:14.234
Thank you.

230
00:14:15.474 --> 00:14:15.814
All right.

231
00:14:17.134 --> 00:14:20.154
Are there any other questions? Then thank you again.

232
00:14:23.334 --> 00:14:26.914
Let's move to the next speaker. Please come up to the

233
00:14:26.994 --> 00:14:28.234
stage, Amin Sabit.

234
00:14:30.014 --> 00:14:30.434
Thank you.

235
00:14:35.754 --> 00:14:37.694
Yep. Hi, everyone. I'm Amin Sabit.

236
00:14:37.814 --> 00:14:41.734
I'm a part of the Charlie Ruden lab at MSK, and it's an honor to

237
00:14:41.774 --> 00:14:45.354
be in front of you here and presenting my work, which is focused on

238
00:14:45.374 --> 00:14:48.384
FOXP2B as a driver of neuroendocrine transformation in the lung.

239
00:14:49.354 --> 00:14:52.934
So no disclosures as well. And lung

240
00:14:53.014 --> 00:14:56.614
cancer, it's the leading cause of cancer-related mortality

241
00:14:56.774 --> 00:14:57.854
worldwide, and it's

242
00:14:58.874 --> 00:15:02.694
broadly divided into non-small cell, which comprises

243
00:15:02.774 --> 00:15:06.314
the far great majority of cases, and the remaining

244
00:15:06.354 --> 00:15:09.834
15% are small cell lung cancer. And

245
00:15:10.014 --> 00:15:13.654
non-small cell lung cancer is further divided into lung adenocarcinoma or

246
00:15:13.694 --> 00:15:17.674
LUAD, small cell carcinoma, as we just heard, and large

247
00:15:17.714 --> 00:15:20.874
cell carcinoma. And while LUADs or lung

248
00:15:20.894 --> 00:15:24.234
adenocarcinoma is the most common subtype of

249
00:15:24.934 --> 00:15:25.544
lung cancer,

250
00:15:26.814 --> 00:15:30.254
it is usually driven by activating mutations in

251
00:15:30.314 --> 00:15:34.174
oncogenetic drivers, especially in MAP kinase pathway, and therefore

252
00:15:34.234 --> 00:15:37.934
has good targeted therapies, while small cell is the most aggressive

253
00:15:38.014 --> 00:15:38.694
subtype of

254
00:15:39.634 --> 00:15:43.324
lung cancer, and it's usually driven by near

255
00:15:43.354 --> 00:15:47.034
universal loss of P53 and Rb, as well as by

256
00:15:47.094 --> 00:15:50.914
expression of lineage-defining master transcription factors

257
00:15:50.974 --> 00:15:54.954
like ASCL1, NEUROD1, and PAX2F3, and also

258
00:15:54.994 --> 00:15:58.954
is characterized by strong expression of neuroendocrine markers

259
00:15:59.394 --> 00:16:02.114
like synaptophysin, chromogranin, and CD56.

260
00:16:03.434 --> 00:16:07.334
Lung adenocarcinoma can actually undergo histologic transformation to small cell

261
00:16:07.474 --> 00:16:10.104
in a process known as neuroendocrine transformation.

262
00:16:10.614 --> 00:16:14.154
And while this is best characterized in EGFR mutant setting under

263
00:16:14.294 --> 00:16:17.974
TKI targeted therapies, where around about 15%

264
00:16:18.334 --> 00:16:20.474
of resistance mechanisms of patients

265
00:16:21.534 --> 00:16:23.294
are due to histologic transformation,

266
00:16:24.794 --> 00:16:28.114
this is not only unique actually to EGFR mutant LUADs and is

267
00:16:28.354 --> 00:16:32.194
observed in EGFR wild type settings like KRAS and

268
00:16:32.294 --> 00:16:35.694
ALK and ROS and RET fusion, and also can be seen

269
00:16:35.734 --> 00:16:37.554
independent of targeted therapies.

270
00:16:38.474 --> 00:16:41.034
Also, neuroendocrine transformation is not unique to the lung.

271
00:16:41.094 --> 00:16:42.394
It's observed in other

272
00:16:43.654 --> 00:16:47.194
cancer contexts, specifically in the prostate where it's really well

273
00:16:47.494 --> 00:16:48.694
characterized and studied.

274
00:16:49.594 --> 00:16:53.074
And as I mentioned with de novo small cell, where

275
00:16:53.134 --> 00:16:57.034
it's a requirement to have P53

276
00:16:57.054 --> 00:17:00.734
and Rb inactivated or lost, this is the same for

277
00:17:00.834 --> 00:17:04.055
transformed small cell. However, it is not sufficient to drive

278
00:17:04.315 --> 00:17:07.874
transformation, and it's believed that

279
00:17:07.914 --> 00:17:11.114
transcription and epigenetic reprogramming are required

280
00:17:11.174 --> 00:17:14.954
to drive transformation. However,

281
00:17:15.694 --> 00:17:19.654
what exactly is the cause of neuroendocrine transformation

282
00:17:19.714 --> 00:17:23.575
on top of P53-Rb loss, as well as also it's believed that

283
00:17:24.035 --> 00:17:27.994
MYC and AKT activation might also be required, but none of these

284
00:17:28.055 --> 00:17:29.674
are sufficient to drive transformation.

285
00:17:30.214 --> 00:17:33.354
So we wanted to know what are further alterations

286
00:17:34.354 --> 00:17:38.034
that are needed to drive small cell transformation in

287
00:17:38.094 --> 00:17:41.344
EGFR mutant LUADs or the triple mutant context with

288
00:17:41.394 --> 00:17:45.154
P53-Rb loss and EGFR mutation. And to answer that, we

289
00:17:45.234 --> 00:17:48.714
wanted to leverage transcriptomic analysis on transforming

290
00:17:49.094 --> 00:17:50.084
clinical samples,

291
00:17:51.034 --> 00:17:54.854
in the hope of identifying novel candidate

292
00:17:54.864 --> 00:17:56.714
drivers of neuroendocrine transformation.

293
00:17:57.554 --> 00:17:59.074
And luckily in the lab,

294
00:18:00.474 --> 00:18:04.334
Joe Chan and Alvaro, through over multiple years, were able to

295
00:18:04.374 --> 00:18:07.214
gather a large cohort of transformed

296
00:18:08.694 --> 00:18:12.034
patient samples and PDXs, and proceeded to do single-cell

297
00:18:12.114 --> 00:18:15.542
RNA-seq on... on the cohort, as well as

298
00:18:16.762 --> 00:18:20.672
never transformed triple mutant LUADs, as

299
00:18:20.742 --> 00:18:22.682
well as de novo small cell lung cancer.

300
00:18:23.342 --> 00:18:27.122
And then also, we're able to further define transforming LUAD,

301
00:18:27.202 --> 00:18:30.722
which is the lung adenocarcinoma compartment in mixed

302
00:18:30.742 --> 00:18:34.382
histology tumors. I forgot to mention that transformed small cell usually

303
00:18:34.462 --> 00:18:36.162
presents as mixed histology tumors.

304
00:18:36.742 --> 00:18:40.102
It will be retaining some of the original LUAD features, as well as the

305
00:18:40.142 --> 00:18:41.262
neuroendocrine population.

306
00:18:42.162 --> 00:18:45.442
And then transforming small cell is the neuroendocrine

307
00:18:45.982 --> 00:18:49.042
compartment of combined histology tumors or post

308
00:18:49.842 --> 00:18:53.522
transformation samples. And by doing differential gene

309
00:18:53.782 --> 00:18:57.442
analysis on the different groups, like LUAD versus transforming

310
00:18:57.502 --> 00:19:01.422
LUAD, and transforming LUAD and transforming small cell, as well as

311
00:19:01.442 --> 00:19:04.622
de novo small cell and transformed small cell,

312
00:19:05.382 --> 00:19:09.282
we hope to see genes that are commonly upregulated through

313
00:19:09.322 --> 00:19:10.742
the transformation pathway.

314
00:19:11.702 --> 00:19:15.542
And then we also wanted to specifically focus on transcription factors

315
00:19:15.582 --> 00:19:19.532
or epigenetic regulators that have been implicated in lineage plasticity or

316
00:19:19.682 --> 00:19:23.622
driving neuronal programs. And then once

317
00:19:23.722 --> 00:19:27.342
we identify candidate drivers, we wanted to validate them in

318
00:19:27.402 --> 00:19:30.502
vitro in our two EGFR mutant cell lines,

319
00:19:31.222 --> 00:19:35.182
PC9 and H1975, and then we would proceed either with the parental cell

320
00:19:35.192 --> 00:19:39.002
lines or induce p53 and Rb inactivation by transducing them

321
00:19:39.042 --> 00:19:42.422
with CYW, which is a plasmid with a dominant negative

322
00:19:42.922 --> 00:19:46.682
p53 and shRNA against Rb, and then we would

323
00:19:46.742 --> 00:19:50.682
overexpress our gene of interest and then evaluate neuroendocrine markers

324
00:19:50.702 --> 00:19:51.522
by Western blot.

325
00:19:52.622 --> 00:19:53.982
And here, just showing

326
00:19:55.142 --> 00:19:58.642
specifically one of the comparisons, de novo small cell to transforming small cell,

327
00:19:58.722 --> 00:20:02.222
where we hope to identify drivers that are unique to transformation.

328
00:20:02.252 --> 00:20:06.202
And in this volcano plot in the top right, you see genes that are

329
00:20:06.282 --> 00:20:09.442
upregulated in transformed small cell versus de novo small cell.

330
00:20:09.902 --> 00:20:13.782
And this is where we initially identified FOX2B as among

331
00:20:13.982 --> 00:20:17.742
one of the most upregulated genes, specifically in transformed small cell.

332
00:20:18.142 --> 00:20:21.662
And the reason we got excited about FOX2B was not

333
00:20:21.722 --> 00:20:25.462
because only it's highly expressed in many of the cluster

334
00:20:25.962 --> 00:20:29.802
UMAP in transformed small cell, and we don't really see expression in de novo

335
00:20:29.902 --> 00:20:33.762
small cell, but also because it's an important

336
00:20:33.772 --> 00:20:37.722
transcription factor in neuronal development, specifically in neural crest cells in

337
00:20:37.782 --> 00:20:40.662
early development, and also it's been shown to be an

338
00:20:41.022 --> 00:20:44.962
oncogenic driver in neuroblastoma, which is a neuroendocrine

339
00:20:44.982 --> 00:20:48.902
tumor as well. So that got us really excited about FOX2B.

340
00:20:48.922 --> 00:20:52.702
And then further computational analysis done in the lab by Joe

341
00:20:52.782 --> 00:20:52.982
and

342
00:20:54.162 --> 00:20:58.072
Mamie showed that among the differentially expressed genes in transformed

343
00:20:58.162 --> 00:21:02.102
small cell as opposed to de novo small cell, FOX2B was among the most

344
00:21:02.502 --> 00:21:05.942
associated with neuroendocrine high signature, as well as least

345
00:21:06.002 --> 00:21:09.622
associated with EGFR signaling. And pathway enrichment

346
00:21:09.702 --> 00:21:13.262
analysis for FOX2B positive versus negative clusters showed high

347
00:21:13.322 --> 00:21:16.542
enrichment of neuronal and neuroendocrine programs in the FOX2B

348
00:21:16.642 --> 00:21:20.502
positive clusters. So then we proceeded

349
00:21:20.542 --> 00:21:23.882
to validate FOX2B as a driver in

350
00:21:24.562 --> 00:21:24.822
our

351
00:21:25.842 --> 00:21:28.602
LUAD EGFR mutant cell lines I mentioned earlier, so

352
00:21:28.782 --> 00:21:30.692
H1975 and PC9,

353
00:21:31.822 --> 00:21:34.462
in the parental and with p53/Rb loss.

354
00:21:35.042 --> 00:21:39.002
And then when we overexpressed FOX2B, one of the early things we saw

355
00:21:39.102 --> 00:21:42.002
was a marked decrease in EGFR signaling.

356
00:21:42.582 --> 00:21:45.782
As we can see here, not only total EGFR, but phospho-EGFR or

357
00:21:45.822 --> 00:21:47.162
active EGFR.

358
00:21:48.002 --> 00:21:51.262
And also we did see some induction of neuroendocrine markers like

359
00:21:51.342 --> 00:21:55.302
synaptophysin, chromogranin, and most importantly, ASCL1, specifically

360
00:21:55.422 --> 00:21:58.382
here actually in the p53/Rb loss context.

361
00:21:58.852 --> 00:22:01.862
And this was highly reproducible across different replicates.

362
00:22:01.922 --> 00:22:05.742
So we were excited about this. However, we did not actually

363
00:22:05.802 --> 00:22:09.642
see histologic transformation or neuroendocrine markers induction on the

364
00:22:09.682 --> 00:22:12.132
level of endogenous small cell lung cancer.

365
00:22:12.772 --> 00:22:16.582
So then we next wondered whether if we inactivate

366
00:22:16.662 --> 00:22:20.222
REST, which is a known master suppressor of neuronal

367
00:22:20.262 --> 00:22:24.062
programs, since REST is active in

368
00:22:24.142 --> 00:22:27.662
lung adenocarcinoma, whether we would be able to drive full histologic

369
00:22:27.702 --> 00:22:31.342
transformation or induction of much stronger neuroendocrine

370
00:22:31.382 --> 00:22:34.942
