00:58:56.180 --> 00:58:59.680
mechanism is essentially pulling the compound into MYC-dependent

995
00:58:59.800 --> 00:59:03.380
condensates to perform whatever the toxic function of the compound is?

996
00:59:03.920 --> 00:59:07.100
Is this one way to interpret the data? Or how are you thinking about this result?

997
00:59:11.240 --> 00:59:12.480
So we

998
00:59:13.680 --> 00:59:17.470
don't have evidence that the compound is being dragged into the MYC

999
00:59:17.520 --> 00:59:20.060
condensates. That is something we're currently looking into.

1000
00:59:20.140 --> 00:59:23.570
It is one possibility. Considering the

1001
00:59:24.280 --> 00:59:27.830
target profile of the molecule, we believe it's happening

1002
00:59:27.880 --> 00:59:30.980
in adjacent to the MYC condensates

1003
00:59:31.020 --> 00:59:32.280
regulating

1004
00:59:33.140 --> 00:59:34.780
the kind of functional outcome.

1005
00:59:36.160 --> 00:59:36.780
Okay. Thank you.

1006
00:59:38.840 --> 00:59:42.149
Yeah, it's true. How does the compound affect MYC protein levels in the

1007
00:59:42.180 --> 00:59:43.620
cell?

1008
00:59:43.680 --> 00:59:47.080
So MYC is well known to be auto-regulating itself, so it's a great

1009
00:59:47.200 --> 00:59:50.800
question. So the MYC compound will also

1010
00:59:50.860 --> 00:59:52.320
reduce the levels of MYC.

1011
00:59:53.120 --> 00:59:53.420
Thanks.

1012
00:59:54.280 --> 00:59:54.680
All right.

1013
00:59:56.620 --> 00:59:59.000
Okay. That's the last question, maybe.

1014
01:00:01.360 --> 01:00:05.000
Doesn't in tumor cells, MYC auto regulation is lost,

1015
01:00:05.180 --> 01:00:08.960
so it's only in a normal cell kind of situation. So you might want to ponder that.

1016
01:00:11.120 --> 01:00:15.040
Okay. Round of applause for the speaker and the exciting discussions. Thank you.

1017
01:00:18.560 --> 01:00:22.520
Then we move to the next speaker, Kyle Egan, who will talk

1018
01:00:22.580 --> 01:00:26.540
about NSD3 is a critical co-factor

1019
01:00:26.600 --> 01:00:30.060
that enables fusion oncoproteins driven 3D genome

1020
01:00:30.120 --> 01:00:32.860
reorganization and activation of

1021
01:00:33.640 --> 01:00:37.190
oncogenic transcriptional programs. Thank you.

1022
01:00:37.720 --> 01:00:41.680
Thank you. I'm Kyle Egan. I'm an assistant professor at Baylor College of Medicine.

1023
01:00:41.720 --> 01:00:45.380
I appreciate the opportunity to talk about some unpublished work from my lab.

1024
01:00:46.340 --> 01:00:50.080
We study fusion-driven cancers and how fusion oncoproteins

1025
01:00:50.220 --> 01:00:54.020
regulate chromatin and transcription to drive the aggressive nature of these

1026
01:00:54.040 --> 01:00:57.556
diseases.So the

1027
01:00:57.576 --> 01:01:01.456
specific fusion-driven cancer I'm going to talk to you about today is a cancer

1028
01:01:01.516 --> 01:01:02.536
called NUT carcinoma.

1029
01:01:03.516 --> 01:01:07.496
It's a squamous cell carcinoma, which is among the most aggressive solid

1030
01:01:07.506 --> 01:01:10.686
tumors. It's found about 50% of the time

1031
01:01:10.776 --> 01:01:14.336
thoracically in the lungs, 40% head and neck, and about

1032
01:01:14.356 --> 01:01:15.935
10% elsewhere in the body.

1033
01:01:16.936 --> 01:01:20.896
It has a median age of diagnosis of 23.6 years, meaning it strikes a

1034
01:01:20.956 --> 01:01:24.756
particularly vulnerable patient population in the AYA gap.

1035
01:01:25.416 --> 01:01:28.476
And unfortunately, NUT carcinoma has no standard of care.

1036
01:01:28.526 --> 01:01:32.456
And due to its exceptional aggressiveness with a median overall survival of

1037
01:01:32.496 --> 01:01:33.656
only six and a half months,

1038
01:01:34.576 --> 01:01:37.736
it's really important to understand more basic biology about how

1039
01:01:38.536 --> 01:01:39.176
this cancer

1040
01:01:40.716 --> 01:01:41.156
functions.

1041
01:01:42.496 --> 01:01:45.796
Compared to many other tumors which are defined anatomically, NUT carcinoma is

1042
01:01:45.836 --> 01:01:49.376
defined molecularly by translocations of the NUTM1 gene, with

1043
01:01:49.436 --> 01:01:53.096
BRD4-NUT being the most common. And what is known about BRD4-NUT

1044
01:01:53.136 --> 01:01:55.156
function is it blocks differentiation.

1045
01:01:57.516 --> 01:02:01.215
Many years ago, we undertook a deep biochemical

1046
01:02:01.256 --> 01:02:04.556
approach to understand how BRD4-NUT functions at the chromatin level.

1047
01:02:05.416 --> 01:02:08.576
And us and collaborators had determined that

1048
01:02:08.936 --> 01:02:12.816
BRD4-NUT coats large regions of chromatin that we call mega

1049
01:02:12.896 --> 01:02:16.756
domains, and through a feed forward mechanism where the bromodomains of

1050
01:02:16.776 --> 01:02:20.496
BRD4 bind to acetylated histones, NUT recruits the

1051
01:02:20.536 --> 01:02:23.816
p300 histone acetyltransferase to result in more acetyl

1052
01:02:23.856 --> 01:02:27.736
deposition, which results in more BRD4-NUT recruitment, creates

1053
01:02:27.776 --> 01:02:31.476
the spreading of BRD4-NUT across chromatin to form these so-called mega

1054
01:02:31.536 --> 01:02:31.996
domains.

1055
01:02:33.176 --> 01:02:36.756
We then used high-throughput chromosome confirmation capture or Hi-C to map

1056
01:02:36.816 --> 01:02:40.556
chromatin interactions in patient-derived NUT carcinoma cell lines.

1057
01:02:40.586 --> 01:02:44.376
And this is just an example of this large genomic data set shown

1058
01:02:44.436 --> 01:02:48.076
here, where we're now looking at different mega domains on

1059
01:02:48.146 --> 01:02:51.696
different chromosomes. So this would be a domain on chromosome 6.

1060
01:02:52.276 --> 01:02:55.936
Similarly, a domain on chromosome 15, where this arrow here is showing the

1061
01:02:55.956 --> 01:02:59.516
chromatin contacts between chromosome six and 15, so interchromosomal

1062
01:02:59.556 --> 01:03:03.456
interactions. And we're interpreting this to mean that the mega domains are coming

1063
01:03:03.496 --> 01:03:07.136
into close physical proximity in 3D space, forming what we call a

1064
01:03:07.196 --> 01:03:09.616
compartment in genomics terms. To

1065
01:03:10.596 --> 01:03:14.586
ground this more in the cell biology of these cancer cells,

1066
01:03:15.036 --> 01:03:18.956
if you stain BRD4-NUT with a antibody or stain the cells with

1067
01:03:19.076 --> 01:03:22.876
H3K27 acetyl, they form distinct foci or condensates in the

1068
01:03:22.936 --> 01:03:26.786
nucleus. And so we think all this gene regulatory processes are

1069
01:03:26.856 --> 01:03:28.496
happening in these nuclear condensates.

1070
01:03:29.176 --> 01:03:33.156
Unfortunately, because it's very difficult to directly target BRD4-NUT, we

1071
01:03:33.456 --> 01:03:36.836
asked another question to better understand the basic mechanisms of these

1072
01:03:37.216 --> 01:03:40.776
altered nuclear organization, or what factors might be cooperating with

1073
01:03:40.796 --> 01:03:41.596
BRD4-NUT.

1074
01:03:42.556 --> 01:03:46.266
So to first approach this, we reanalyzed mass spectrometry

1075
01:03:46.356 --> 01:03:49.976
data from two different cell lines, just simple, naive

1076
01:03:50.116 --> 01:03:54.016
293T cells that are induced to express BRD4-NUT, as well as a

1077
01:03:54.056 --> 01:03:57.776
patient-derived cell line with a epitope tag on BRD4-NUT so we can identify

1078
01:03:57.916 --> 01:04:01.616
common interactors. And we identified many, many

1079
01:04:01.716 --> 01:04:03.256
proteins that interact with BRD4-NUT.

1080
01:04:03.296 --> 01:04:05.816
But what stood out to us was this protein NSD3.

1081
01:04:06.456 --> 01:04:10.156
And we particularly focused on NSD3 because NUT carcinoma is

1082
01:04:10.176 --> 01:04:13.556
defined by NUTM1 translocations, with NSD3-NUT

1083
01:04:13.596 --> 01:04:15.936
being one of those translocations.

1084
01:04:15.996 --> 01:04:19.656
So the biochemical data was agreeing with clinical data from

1085
01:04:19.696 --> 01:04:21.636
patients with this NSD3-NUT fusion.

1086
01:04:21.996 --> 01:04:24.746
And although this is a very interesting question in and of itself, I'm just going

1087
01:04:24.756 --> 01:04:28.376
to focus on the function of NSD3 in BRD4-NUT positive

1088
01:04:28.456 --> 01:04:28.816
cells.

1089
01:04:29.996 --> 01:04:33.956
So we went ahead and used CRISPR interference or CRISPRi to knock down

1090
01:04:34.076 --> 01:04:34.736
NSD3,

1091
01:04:35.596 --> 01:04:37.056
getting good knockdown on chromatin.

1092
01:04:37.336 --> 01:04:40.636
NSD3 is a histone H3K36 methyltransferase.

1093
01:04:41.036 --> 01:04:44.336
It deposits H3K36 dimethyl. When we knock down

1094
01:04:44.816 --> 01:04:48.776
NSD3, we see loss of the H3K36 dimethyl

1095
01:04:48.796 --> 01:04:52.036
mark, where BRD4-NUT is also bound on chromatin.

1096
01:04:52.466 --> 01:04:56.236
And to summarize this on genome-wide, we've normalized each of the mega domains to

1097
01:04:56.276 --> 01:05:00.136
the same size, plus a constant amount of flanking DNA, and then color-coded them

1098
01:05:00.196 --> 01:05:04.036
for each of the different epitopes that we're profiling by cut and run, seeing

1099
01:05:04.076 --> 01:05:07.956
loss of the K36 dimethyl. We also see a reduction of

1100
01:05:07.976 --> 01:05:11.796
BRD4-NUT occupancy on chromatin within the mega domains, but

1101
01:05:12.516 --> 01:05:16.336
not striking changes in H3K27 acetyl levels.

1102
01:05:18.216 --> 01:05:22.176
We then went on to profile how NSD3 might affect the BRD4-NUT

1103
01:05:22.216 --> 01:05:22.896
condensates.

1104
01:05:23.736 --> 01:05:27.636
And just for the case of time, I didn't have time to show you, but NSD3 is also

1105
01:05:27.756 --> 01:05:30.076
colocalizing with BRD4-NUT in condensates.

1106
01:05:30.776 --> 01:05:34.436
On the single-cell level, we see loss, obviously, of NSD3 because we're depleting

1107
01:05:34.496 --> 01:05:38.236
it. When we knock down NSD3, we see a reduced

1108
01:05:38.276 --> 01:05:42.156
intensity of the BRD4-NUT condensates and an increased number of condensates, as

1109
01:05:42.196 --> 01:05:46.026
well as for the H3K27 acetyl, which is a second mark to robustly

1110
01:05:46.036 --> 01:05:49.656
confirm this. And the way we're looking at this in an unbiased way is to quantify

1111
01:05:49.696 --> 01:05:53.116
both the mean intensity per condensate and then the number of

1112
01:05:53.136 --> 01:05:57.116
condensates per nucleus. And we see that these two parameters are moving in

1113
01:05:57.196 --> 01:06:00.556
opposite directions. When we deplete NSD3, we're seeing a decrease in the

1114
01:06:00.936 --> 01:06:04.816
intensity per condensate and an increase in mean number of condensates,

1115
01:06:04.856 --> 01:06:08.476
suggesting that the condensates are getting dispersed when we knock down NSD3 in

1116
01:06:08.496 --> 01:06:09.016
these cells.

1117
01:06:11.516 --> 01:06:14.936
We then, to understand how these two changes relate to 3D genome

1118
01:06:14.996 --> 01:06:18.916
organization, we performed Hi-C on NSD3-depleted cells and kind of walk you

1119
01:06:18.956 --> 01:06:21.896
through this slide, which I understand has a lot of data on it.

1120
01:06:23.116 --> 01:06:26.956
So this is a Hi-C contact map for human chromosome 8, just around the

1121
01:06:27.016 --> 01:06:29.816
MYC locus. MYC is actually right here on the far side of this

1122
01:06:30.616 --> 01:06:34.136
window. Below the diagonal is the Hi-C data from the

1123
01:06:34.216 --> 01:06:37.936
non-targeting control cells with a mirror image above the

1124
01:06:37.976 --> 01:06:40.876
diagonal, but this time it's for the NSD3 knockdown cells.

1125
01:06:41.416 --> 01:06:45.176
With the cut-and-run data for NSD3 knockdown cells along the x-axis

1126
01:06:45.536 --> 01:06:48.316
and the cut-and-run data for the non-target cells along the y-axis.

1127
01:06:48.396 --> 01:06:51.476
And just to kind of give you an idea of the scale of the chromatin interactions

1128
01:06:51.516 --> 01:06:55.496
we're looking at, we are specifically interested in chromatin interactions

1129
01:06:55.536 --> 01:06:59.476
between the BRD4-NUT mega domains, which are these black tick

1130
01:06:59.536 --> 01:07:03.356
boxes, which are shown as these black boxes on the Hi-C contact

1131
01:07:03.416 --> 01:07:06.036
map. So these are occurring over tens of megabases in this

1132
01:07:06.096 --> 01:07:09.964
window.Because admittedly these are very

1133
01:07:10.064 --> 01:07:13.784
small and these large maps, we're going to blow up each of these individual

1134
01:07:13.824 --> 01:07:17.784
interactions with the knockdown on the left and the non-target control on

1135
01:07:17.804 --> 01:07:21.584
the right, where you can see the cut-and-run data consistent with what I showed you

1136
01:07:21.644 --> 01:07:25.544
two slides ago. But we're also seeing a decrease in chromatin interactions in the

1137
01:07:25.584 --> 01:07:29.364
knockdown sample compared to the non-target control, both here at this locus,

1138
01:07:29.764 --> 01:07:32.924
but also at the three other windows within this

1139
01:07:33.804 --> 01:07:37.604
region on chromosome eight. We've also expanded the analysis genome-wide

1140
01:07:37.664 --> 01:07:41.524
using these pile-up analysis, where we're basically looking at the

1141
01:07:42.304 --> 01:07:45.944
signal of the interaction intensity in the non-target control cells versus the

1142
01:07:46.044 --> 01:07:49.544
NSD3 cells averaged over all 150 CIS

1143
01:07:49.644 --> 01:07:53.464
interactions. And we see about a twofold decrease in chromatin interactions,

1144
01:07:53.864 --> 01:07:57.484
which are also then just statistically quantified here, but looking at the box plot

1145
01:07:57.494 --> 01:07:59.144
when we're looking at individual contacts.

1146
01:08:00.984 --> 01:08:04.444
Okay, so what happens to gene expression when we knock down NSD3?

1147
01:08:05.444 --> 01:08:08.884
This is just a simple volcano plot looking at fold-change of gene expression of

1148
01:08:08.944 --> 01:08:12.624
NSD3 versus P-value. And we're not seeing tons of gene

1149
01:08:12.663 --> 01:08:16.264
expression changes, which I think is a little reassuring that we see NSD3

1150
01:08:16.445 --> 01:08:18.824
mostly in the mega domains, not elsewhere in the genome.

1151
01:08:19.364 --> 01:08:23.264
And I've color-coded the gene expression changes here, such that the mega domain

1152
01:08:23.324 --> 01:08:27.315
genes are shown in purple, which seems to be like there's a bias for downregulation

1153
01:08:27.344 --> 01:08:31.204
of the mega domain genes, which is more rigorously shown here with the

1154
01:08:31.264 --> 01:08:35.094
GSEA analysis, showing a downregulation of those genes in the BRD4

1155
01:08:35.324 --> 01:08:39.084
mega domains. And also using unbiased GSEA analysis, we're seeing

1156
01:08:39.124 --> 01:08:42.985
an enrichment for downregulation of MYC target genes, which is

1157
01:08:43.025 --> 01:08:46.224
significant for this cancer because nut carcinoma is known to be a MYC-driven

1158
01:08:46.364 --> 01:08:46.744
tumor.

1159
01:08:48.924 --> 01:08:52.464
Lastly, at a very broad functional level, we looked at

1160
01:08:52.784 --> 01:08:55.405
what happens to the cells when we deplete NSD3.

1161
01:08:55.644 --> 01:08:59.424
Nut carcinoma cells, as I mentioned, are a very poorly differentiated tumor.

1162
01:08:59.864 --> 01:09:03.844
These cells are usually very small cells with very little cytoplasm compared to

1163
01:09:03.864 --> 01:09:07.605
the nucleus. When we knock down the cells, the cells flatten, the nuclei become

1164
01:09:07.704 --> 01:09:11.424
larger. They upregulate the KRT7 epithelial

1165
01:09:11.485 --> 01:09:13.924
specific differentiation marker, and we see a modest

1166
01:09:15.124 --> 01:09:16.384
downregulation of cell growth.

1167
01:09:18.284 --> 01:09:21.584
So, in summary, we've identified NSD3 as a structural

1168
01:09:21.724 --> 01:09:25.714
cofactor that stabilizes oncogenic chromatin organization and

1169
01:09:25.804 --> 01:09:29.584
the malignant cell state. It does this by promoting both BRD4

1170
01:09:29.824 --> 01:09:33.304
occupancy on chromatin, as well as depositing H3K36

1171
01:09:33.324 --> 01:09:36.864
dimethyl. We think it's helping to reinforce the BRD4 nuclear

1172
01:09:36.905 --> 01:09:40.724
condensates and to help enable the long-range chromatin contacts that are

1173
01:09:40.744 --> 01:09:42.445
driven by this fusion oncoprotein.

1174
01:09:43.004 --> 01:09:46.485
It's sustaining oncogenic transcription within the mega domains, which is also

1175
01:09:46.525 --> 01:09:49.565
helping to preserve the poorly differentiated state.

1176
01:09:50.124 --> 01:09:53.884
And we think that this is an interesting new direction because NSD3 is a tractable

1177
01:09:53.905 --> 01:09:57.684
therapeutic. There are small molecules coming online

1178
01:09:57.744 --> 01:10:01.624
that inhibit NSD3, both catalytically and non-catalytically.

1179
01:10:01.764 --> 01:10:05.724
And we think this might be important due to the lack of standard of care in this

1180
01:10:05.784 --> 01:10:06.204
cancer.

1181
01:10:10.624 --> 01:10:12.664
Lastly, just wanted to acknowledge the lab.

1182
01:10:12.704 --> 01:10:16.484
This work was driven by a graduate student, Yi-Hung Chen, in the lab,

1183
01:10:16.564 --> 01:10:18.864
supported by John Collette, Krupa,

1184
01:10:19.024 --> 01:10:22.544
Sampat, Adela, Sarah, and Selena, as well as

1185
01:10:22.624 --> 01:10:25.954
former lab members. We have a great collaboration with Christopher French at

1186
01:10:25.964 --> 01:10:27.144
Brigham and Women's Hospital,

1187
01:10:28.064 --> 01:10:30.024
and I appreciate it for funding sources.

1188
01:10:30.224 --> 01:10:31.804
And with that, I'm happy to take questions.

1189
01:10:36.584 --> 01:10:38.344
Thank you very much. First question, please.

1190
01:10:38.564 --> 01:10:40.984
Hi, Jonathan Licht, Van Andel Institute.

1191
01:10:41.084 --> 01:10:42.644
Thank you for a very clear

1192
01:10:44.884 --> 01:10:46.444
presentation, very nice data.

1193
01:10:48.264 --> 01:10:50.884
The looping change is kind of modest.

1194
01:10:50.924 --> 01:10:54.844
It's like half down, and so what that means on a

1195
01:10:54.884 --> 01:10:57.384
cell basis is the loop formed or didn't form.

1196
01:10:57.484 --> 01:10:59.304
It's like you can't half form a loop, right?

1197
01:10:59.384 --> 01:11:02.024
So it means some cells are forming a loop and some are not.

1198
01:11:02.584 --> 01:11:03.684
And in that regard,

1199
01:11:05.064 --> 01:11:08.644
how heterogeneous is the phenotypic response or some cells that

1200
01:11:08.844 --> 01:11:12.824
still form the loop, still undifferentiated, ones

1201
01:11:12.844 --> 01:11:16.024
that form the loop, whatever changes, and they differentiate?

1202
01:11:16.104 --> 01:11:19.944
That's one question. And then what's the redundancy with the other

1203
01:11:20.024 --> 01:11:23.954
NSDs? And have you tried some double knockouts or things

1204
01:11:23.984 --> 01:11:27.963
like K36M, which kind of blocks them all or things like that?

1205
01:11:27.984 --> 01:11:31.764
Yep. All great questions. So yeah, the Hi-C data is population

1206
01:11:32.204 --> 01:11:36.044
scale data, so we can't drill down to

1207
01:11:36.264 --> 01:11:39.254
sometimes the loop is down. It seems it is about down about

1208
01:11:39.284 --> 01:11:40.344
twofold.

1209
01:11:41.924 --> 01:11:45.784
But without doing like a FISH experiment to actually look at locus by locus

1210
01:11:45.824 --> 01:11:49.724
levels, we don't really know. It's interesting that the condensate

1211
01:11:49.764 --> 01:11:53.594
destabilization is about twofold by looking at other measurements, and

1212
01:11:53.664 --> 01:11:57.624
the looping's down twofold. It's kind of like things are tracking internally like

1213
01:11:57.764 --> 01:11:59.764
that, which was a little more reassuring.

1214
01:12:01.224 --> 01:12:04.284
The cell state, this is not, as you saw from the proliferation data, this is not

1215
01:12:04.324 --> 01:12:07.124
totally slowing the cells down. We do generally see that

1216
01:12:07.204 --> 01:12:11.084
they're in a more differentiated state across the

1217
01:12:11.124 --> 01:12:14.914
cell population. In terms of the other NSDs, this is an interesting

1218
01:12:14.964 --> 01:12:18.944
question. They're all expressed in

1219
01:12:18.954 --> 01:12:22.764
the cells that we've tested. None of them are localizing to the condensates.

1220
01:12:23.924 --> 01:12:26.064
We've had difficulties knocking down some of them.

1221
01:12:26.124 --> 01:12:28.424
