Division of Cancer Epidemiology and Genetics, where I'm in the Laboratory of

1471
01:27:46.768 --> 01:27:48.748
Translational Genomics, where I'm a post-doc.

1472
01:27:49.408 --> 01:27:53.368
Today, I'm going to discuss a project that started from variation at the TERT locus

1473
01:27:53.868 --> 01:27:57.848
and led us to previously unrecognized antisense transcript regulated

1474
01:27:57.858 --> 01:28:01.538
by RNA methylation with downstream effects on DNA replication

1475
01:28:01.608 --> 01:28:04.487
programs and cancer cell growth.

1476
01:28:05.368 --> 01:28:06.328
I have no disclosures.

1477
01:28:07.948 --> 01:28:11.688
So TERT lies within chromosome 5p15.33, which is a

1478
01:28:11.728 --> 01:28:13.928
well-known multi-cancer GWAS locus.

1479
01:28:14.468 --> 01:28:17.688
In genome-wide association studies, we compare the frequency of common

1480
01:28:18.348 --> 01:28:21.828
genetic variants between cases and controls, and we look for those that are

1481
01:28:21.868 --> 01:28:23.948
statistically enriched in cases.

1482
01:28:24.028 --> 01:28:27.688
On a Manhattan plot, each dot is one tested variant, and peaks mark

1483
01:28:27.698 --> 01:28:29.148
regions associated with risk.

1484
01:28:29.948 --> 01:28:33.788
Importantly, the top SNP at a peak is often a signal for a linked variant

1485
01:28:33.988 --> 01:28:37.788
and is not necessarily causal, which is why functional studies are often

1486
01:28:37.828 --> 01:28:38.108
needed.

1487
01:28:40.208 --> 01:28:44.008
GWAS panels are optimized for SNPs or single nucleotide polymorphisms,

1488
01:28:44.448 --> 01:28:47.788
but they often under-capture tandem repeats and other structural variants.

1489
01:28:48.688 --> 01:28:52.348
By using long-read sequencing, we can directly visualize multiple

1490
01:28:52.448 --> 01:28:56.388
intronic VNTRs or variable number tandem repeats within the TERT

1491
01:28:56.438 --> 01:28:56.788
locus.

1492
01:28:58.228 --> 01:29:02.078
In our prior work, we implicated VNTR6-1 in intron six as a

1493
01:29:02.148 --> 01:29:04.038
proxy for some of these GWAS signals.

1494
01:29:05.068 --> 01:29:08.988
And here we're focusing on VNTR2-1 in intron two of TERT, which is a

1495
01:29:09.048 --> 01:29:12.758
42 base pair repeat and is highly polymorphic in the population.

1496
01:29:14.268 --> 01:29:17.548
Once we prioritize VNTR2-1, we inspected a sequence itself

1497
01:29:18.328 --> 01:29:20.858
and asked whether it might encode overlooked functional roles.

1498
01:29:22.368 --> 01:29:25.868
On the antisense strand, we found a Kozak sequence and start codon

1499
01:29:25.928 --> 01:29:29.808
upstream of this repeat and a stop codon downstream, predicting a

1500
01:29:29.848 --> 01:29:33.548
long open reading frame whose length scales with VNTR2-1

1501
01:29:33.588 --> 01:29:34.177
repeat number.

1502
01:29:35.088 --> 01:29:38.308
That prompted us to ask whether an antisense transcript is expressed from the

1503
01:29:38.328 --> 01:29:42.237
region and what function it has. First, we tested whether this predicted

1504
01:29:42.328 --> 01:29:45.328
transcript is real and expressed in cells.

1505
01:29:45.848 --> 01:29:49.388
We first noticed antisense transcription across intron two in tumor

1506
01:29:49.508 --> 01:29:50.338
RNA sequencing.

1507
01:29:51.928 --> 01:29:55.648
To validate orientation, we performed five prime RACE followed by long-read

1508
01:29:55.688 --> 01:29:59.597
nanopore sequencing, which produced reads mapping to VNTR2-1 in

1509
01:29:59.628 --> 01:30:00.868
the antisense orientation.

1510
01:30:02.508 --> 01:30:06.488
Finally, RNA FISH visualized VNTR2-1 antisense in cells

1511
01:30:06.848 --> 01:30:10.048
with a no probe and knockout controls supporting the specificity.

1512
01:30:10.868 --> 01:30:14.808
Together, these assays support VNTR2-1 as expressed as a transcript.

1513
01:30:15.708 --> 01:30:19.428
Once we had a validated transcript, the next question was: What within this repeat

1514
01:30:19.488 --> 01:30:20.728
might regulate this expression?

1515
01:30:22.508 --> 01:30:25.788
Each 42 base pair repeat of VNTR2-1 contains

1516
01:30:25.828 --> 01:30:29.318
DRACH motifs, which are the consensus motifs recognized by

1517
01:30:29.408 --> 01:30:30.408
M6A writers

1518
01:30:31.408 --> 01:30:35.188
such as METTL3 during M6A modification, with a number of predicted

1519
01:30:35.268 --> 01:30:37.528
M6A sites scaling with the repeat count.

1520
01:30:38.568 --> 01:30:42.188
Since M6A modifications can tune RNA stability and

1521
01:30:42.228 --> 01:30:46.148
translation, this suggested an epitranscriptomic mechanism encoded

1522
01:30:46.168 --> 01:30:47.528
directly by the repeat sequence.

1523
01:30:49.268 --> 01:30:52.028
Next, we tested whether the repeat-encoded motifs are functional.

1524
01:30:53.968 --> 01:30:57.568
To do this, we cloned VNTR2-1 consensus repeats into an M6A

1525
01:30:57.648 --> 01:31:01.578
deficient CyCheck-2 luciferase reporter, comparing constructs

1526
01:31:01.608 --> 01:31:04.948
with intact motifs to motif disrupted

1527
01:31:05.018 --> 01:31:08.088
M6A-null repeats. In bladder cancer cell line

1528
01:31:08.208 --> 01:31:12.078
UM-UC-3, the M6A intact construct significantly increased

1529
01:31:12.128 --> 01:31:14.888
luciferase activity relative to the null construct.

1530
01:31:15.948 --> 01:31:19.108
Then, to test M6A writer dependence, we treated cells with

1531
01:31:19.208 --> 01:31:22.108
STM2457, which is a METTL3 inhibitor.

1532
01:31:23.228 --> 01:31:26.548
STM2457 selectively reduced activity from the

1533
01:31:26.928 --> 01:31:30.368
M6A intact construct, while the null construct was comparatively

1534
01:31:30.408 --> 01:31:34.368
insensitive, supporting a METTL3-dependent mechanism encoded by

1535
01:31:34.388 --> 01:31:38.124
the repeat.Because M6A often affects translation,

1536
01:31:38.404 --> 01:31:41.964
we asked whether VNTR2-1AS is translationally competent.

1537
01:31:43.624 --> 01:31:47.234
We generated a flag-tagged construct containing the native Kozak sequence,

1538
01:31:47.484 --> 01:31:51.084
start codon, and several VNTR2-1 repeats, along

1539
01:31:51.124 --> 01:31:54.564
with a matched control in which the start codon was mutated from

1540
01:31:54.604 --> 01:31:55.824
ATG to ATT.

1541
01:31:57.024 --> 01:32:00.864
On Western blot, the wild-type construct produced a detectable flag signal, whereas

1542
01:32:00.904 --> 01:32:04.004
the start codon mutant did not. This supports that the

1543
01:32:04.064 --> 01:32:07.704
VNTR2-1AS sequence is sufficient to

1544
01:32:07.824 --> 01:32:09.824
initiate translation in mammalian cells.

1545
01:32:10.884 --> 01:32:13.004
We then asked whether this endogenous RNA

1546
01:32:13.304 --> 01:32:16.604
localization is compatible with translation.

1547
01:32:18.064 --> 01:32:21.384
We performed RNA FISH for VNTR2-1 antisense RNA

1548
01:32:21.784 --> 01:32:25.624
together with immunofluorescence for RPS3, which is a ribosomal marker,

1549
01:32:26.524 --> 01:32:29.124
and calnexin, a rough endoplasmic reticulum marker.

1550
01:32:29.924 --> 01:32:33.804
The VNTR2-1AS signal is predominantly perinuclear and is

1551
01:32:33.844 --> 01:32:36.844
found in regions enriched for these translation-associated markers.

1552
01:32:37.424 --> 01:32:41.064
While this does not prove translation, it places the endogenous RNA in a

1553
01:32:41.104 --> 01:32:43.184
translation-compatible cellular context.

1554
01:32:44.984 --> 01:32:48.954
With evidence for both METTL3-sensitive regulation and translational competence,

1555
01:32:49.124 --> 01:32:53.064
we asked what VNTR2-1AS does functionally in cancer cells.

1556
01:32:55.484 --> 01:32:58.664
To do this, we performed RNA sequencing as a

1557
01:32:58.674 --> 01:33:01.804
hypothesis-generating screen after altering the levels of

1558
01:33:01.824 --> 01:33:05.784
VNTR2-1AS. In our overexpression arm, we transiently

1559
01:33:05.844 --> 01:33:09.644
overexpressed VNTR2-1AS in A549 and compared with a

1560
01:33:09.684 --> 01:33:10.464
GFP control.

1561
01:33:12.084 --> 01:33:16.024
Using RNA-seq followed by gene set enrichment analysis, we observed enrichment

1562
01:33:16.084 --> 01:33:20.044
for both cell cycle and DNA replication gene sets relative to control.

1563
01:33:21.664 --> 01:33:25.424
To test whether those pathway-level shifts translate to a measurable phenotype, we

1564
01:33:25.444 --> 01:33:27.804
used Acceligen's real-time cell analysis.

1565
01:33:28.244 --> 01:33:32.144
And when cells are added, they attach and spread, which impedes electrical signal,

1566
01:33:32.304 --> 01:33:36.204
and the instrument reports this as cell index over time, with higher

1567
01:33:36.264 --> 01:33:37.784
curves representing faster growth.

1568
01:33:41.124 --> 01:33:44.504
To test whether this signal is reciprocal, we asked whether deleting the

1569
01:33:44.564 --> 01:33:48.354
VNTR2-1 region via CRISPR-Cas9 produced the opposite

1570
01:33:48.424 --> 01:33:52.184
shift phenotype. Here we're looking at VNTR2-1 knockout

1571
01:33:52.204 --> 01:33:53.904
versus UMEC3 wild type.

1572
01:33:55.664 --> 01:33:59.564
In RNA-seq followed by GSEA, we see depletion of cell cycle and

1573
01:33:59.604 --> 01:34:01.084
DNA replication pathways

1574
01:34:02.284 --> 01:34:03.244
compared to wild type.

1575
01:34:04.564 --> 01:34:08.304
Functionally, this corresponds to slower real-time proliferation in the knockout

1576
01:34:08.344 --> 01:34:09.464
cells by Acceligen.

1577
01:34:11.164 --> 01:34:15.124
And importantly, after synchronization, BrdU incorporation

1578
01:34:15.144 --> 01:34:18.424
was reduced in the knockout cells, supporting reduced S-phase DNA

1579
01:34:18.464 --> 01:34:20.984
synthesis and a replication-linked defect.

1580
01:34:22.964 --> 01:34:26.544
Overall, the transcriptomic reciprocity predicted a growth and replication

1581
01:34:26.564 --> 01:34:30.224
phenotype, and the functional assays validate that direction.

1582
01:34:30.264 --> 01:34:33.554
Finally, we asked whether that downstream program depends on that

1583
01:34:33.604 --> 01:34:35.273
translational competence.

1584
01:34:36.844 --> 01:34:40.724
To do this, we compared the VNTR2-1AS flag construct to a matched

1585
01:34:40.804 --> 01:34:41.704
start codon mutant.

1586
01:34:43.244 --> 01:34:46.764
In the RNA-seq and GSEA comparison, the key point is that DNA

1587
01:34:46.804 --> 01:34:50.744
replication enrichment is retained while the cell cycle signal drops out

1588
01:34:50.864 --> 01:34:52.584
and is no longer supported by FDR.

1589
01:34:53.544 --> 01:34:57.484
That points to DNA replication as the more robust pathway-level output

1590
01:34:57.504 --> 01:34:59.254
of the translation-competent construct.

1591
01:35:00.744 --> 01:35:04.584
Consistent with that, in Acceligen, the ATG construct shows the strongest

1592
01:35:04.624 --> 01:35:07.664
phenotype, while the ATT mutant is similar to control.

1593
01:35:08.524 --> 01:35:12.244
This start codon control supports a translation-dependent contribution and

1594
01:35:12.264 --> 01:35:15.304
reinforces DNA replication as a major downstream output.

1595
01:35:16.824 --> 01:35:19.984
We see that the pathway is more enriched in this comparison compared to the

1596
01:35:20.024 --> 01:35:21.164
comparison with GFP.

1597
01:35:22.344 --> 01:35:25.284
And the overlapping genes in both of those comparisons are related to DNA

1598
01:35:25.324 --> 01:35:27.724
replication, initiation, and stabilization.

1599
01:35:29.744 --> 01:35:31.544
To close, here are the main take-home points.

1600
01:35:32.484 --> 01:35:36.284
VNTR2-1 is a polymorphic intronic repeat within intron two of

1601
01:35:36.304 --> 01:35:40.224
TERT that serves as a proxy to GWAS signals in the region and acts as a

1602
01:35:40.264 --> 01:35:41.824
functional element at this locus.

1603
01:35:42.904 --> 01:35:45.884
It encodes a previously unrecognized antisense transcript,

1604
01:35:46.144 --> 01:35:49.844
VNTR2-1AS, with a repeat length scaled open reading

1605
01:35:49.924 --> 01:35:50.764
frame.

1606
01:35:51.624 --> 01:35:55.424
This open reading frame contains M6A motifs that are functional and

1607
01:35:55.484 --> 01:35:56.504
METTL3 sensitive.

1608
01:35:58.464 --> 01:36:02.044
And the transcript is translationally competent and its translation shifts DNA

1609
01:36:02.064 --> 01:36:05.344
replication, proliferation, and S-phase DNA synthesis.

1610
01:36:07.184 --> 01:36:10.724
Overall, this suggests that a polymorphic intronic repeat at TERT

1611
01:36:10.844 --> 01:36:14.724
encodes a layered RNA and translational mechanism that influences replication

1612
01:36:14.804 --> 01:36:16.504
and cancer-relevant growth phenotypes.

